THE COUNTRY Council ofRua Maselu Tupua, with his sword raised, as he crosses the ala levu (main road) in Apia during Samoa’s Independence Day parade held on Wednesday. Photo: Ory WongSamoa marked 98 years since gaining the right to self-governance through responsible representation in the Legislative Assembly at the start of its journey towards Independence from British rule in 1920. But it was in 1962 after New Zealand conquered Samoa following a guerrilla war that it received its ultimate goal of full independence. Foreign Minister Tuilaepa Sailele Malielegaoi told parliament on Wednesday, on an up-beat note, that Samoa today is a happier nation with people enjoying longer, healthier lives and an ease of traveling in and out of the country compared to other places. “Some people describe Samoa as the gate way to paradise and they are very correct,” he said.
